Based on Theorem 3, we proceed to analyze the stability property of the empirical risk and the
convergence rate of the generalization error in expectation. Let S = {(x(1), y(1)), и и и , (x(n), y(n))} denote the sample set in which the samples are i.i.d. drawn from D. When the optimal solution wn to problem (1) is computed by deterministic algorithms, the generalization error is defined as g = J^n(wn) - J (wn). But one usually employs randomized algorithms, e.g. stochastic gradient descent (SGD), for computing wn. In this case, stability and generalization error in expectation
defined in Definition 3 are more applicable.

Definition 3. (Stability and generalization in expectation) (Vapnik & Vapnik, 1998; Shalev-Shwartz

et al., 2010; Gonen & Shalev-Shwartz, 2017) Assume a randomized algorithm A is employed,

